WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.042 --> 00:00:02.542
(logo chimes)

2
00:00:08.496 --> 00:00:12.305
<v Announcer>So this is the first of</v>

3
00:00:12.305 --> 00:00:15.817
a series of lecture on pulmonary.

4
00:00:15.817 --> 00:00:19.223
And remember, this is 13% of the questions.

5
00:00:19.223 --> 00:00:20.499
<v Dr. Conner>At least.</v>

6
00:00:20.499 --> 00:00:22.687
So let's get started with pulmonary.

7
00:00:22.687 --> 00:00:23.956
This morning we're gonna discuss

8
00:00:23.956 --> 00:00:27.373
obstructive diseases, starting with COPD.

9
00:00:28.577 --> 00:00:30.467
Now, what's new here is of course

10
00:00:30.467 --> 00:00:31.547
the GOLD guidelines.

11
00:00:31.547 --> 00:00:33.699
How many are familiar with GOLD?

12
00:00:33.699 --> 00:00:36.146
This is the Global Obstructive Lung Disease.

13
00:00:36.146 --> 00:00:38.880
This is the NIH and the World Health Organization

14
00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:40.865
together that every year

15
00:00:40.865 --> 00:00:43.002
update the COPD guidelines.

16
00:00:43.002 --> 00:00:44.740
Now, you'll see these guidelines

17
00:00:44.740 --> 00:00:47.724
a lot in these presentations here at the AAFP.

18
00:00:47.724 --> 00:00:50.503
Pay attention because the boards

19
00:00:50.503 --> 00:00:52.502
love to ask you

20
00:00:52.502 --> 00:00:55.455
questions about any updated guidelines

21
00:00:55.455 --> 00:00:57.275
within the last several years.

22
00:00:57.275 --> 00:00:59.746
So when you see a presenter talk about

23
00:00:59.746 --> 00:01:02.329
a new guideline, this is very important.

24
00:01:02.329 --> 00:01:03.966
When you hear the term,

25
00:01:03.966 --> 00:01:05.943
US Preventive Services Task Force

26
00:01:05.943 --> 00:01:07.639
Guide Recommendation,

27
00:01:07.639 --> 00:01:09.431
always pay careful attention.

28
00:01:09.431 --> 00:01:12.022
So these are the updated gold guidelines.

29
00:01:12.022 --> 00:01:14.874
So COPD, Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease.

30
00:01:14.874 --> 00:01:16.246
Currently the fifth leading cause of death

31
00:01:16.246 --> 00:01:17.079
in the US.

32
00:01:17.079 --> 00:01:19.409
Used to be number three.

33
00:01:19.409 --> 00:01:22.903
Well in 2017, accidental injury deaths

34
00:01:22.903 --> 00:01:24.157
took over the third spot.

35
00:01:24.157 --> 00:01:26.175
Do we know why?

36
00:01:26.175 --> 00:01:29.242
Because of a surge in opioid-related deaths.

37
00:01:29.242 --> 00:01:33.001
In 2020 COVID-19 took over the third spot,

38
00:01:33.001 --> 00:01:35.293
but now we're back to the new normal,

39
00:01:35.293 --> 00:01:37.001
and cardiovascular number one,

40
00:01:37.001 --> 00:01:38.504
cancer number two,

41
00:01:38.504 --> 00:01:40.304
and accidental injury deaths

42
00:01:40.304 --> 00:01:43.120
due to a surge in opioid-related fentanyl deaths

43
00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:44.261
is now the third leading cause of death

44
00:01:44.261 --> 00:01:45.337
in this country.

45
00:01:45.337 --> 00:01:46.490
Interesting.

46
00:01:46.490 --> 00:01:48.192
Now, COPD is common,

47
00:01:48.192 --> 00:01:49.803
preventable and treatable.

48
00:01:49.803 --> 00:01:51.948
It's underdiagnosed and misdiagnosed.

49
00:01:51.948 --> 00:01:54.442
So we need to do a bit better job.

50
00:01:54.442 --> 00:01:56.961
I like to think of COPD

51
00:01:56.961 --> 00:02:00.044
as a complicated course of an illness

52
00:02:01.175 --> 00:02:05.486
that it results in obstruction and inflammation.

53
00:02:05.486 --> 00:02:06.965
So with COPD,

54
00:02:06.965 --> 00:02:09.833
you have chronic progressive

55
00:02:09.833 --> 00:02:12.031
airflow obstruction, as opposed to asthma,

56
00:02:12.031 --> 00:02:13.851
which would be chronic reversible

57
00:02:13.851 --> 00:02:16.101
airflow obstruction, right.

58
00:02:17.583 --> 00:02:19.412
This is a complicated factor.

59
00:02:19.412 --> 00:02:21.496
Here you've got internal genetic issues,

60
00:02:21.496 --> 00:02:23.388
like many issues in medicine,

61
00:02:23.388 --> 00:02:25.320
say diabetes for example.

62
00:02:25.320 --> 00:02:27.435
And then you have environmental insults,

63
00:02:27.435 --> 00:02:30.102
in this case, inhaled irritants.

64
00:02:31.327 --> 00:02:34.327
And then these things can combine over time,

65
00:02:34.327 --> 00:02:36.143
and depending on these factors,

66
00:02:36.143 --> 00:02:38.393
a patient may develop COPD.

67
00:02:39.476 --> 00:02:41.250
The biggest environmental insult

68
00:02:41.250 --> 00:02:42.421
that we'll see in this country is smoking.

69
00:02:42.421 --> 00:02:43.254
Smoking, smoking,

70
00:02:43.254 --> 00:02:45.090
smoking is the number one cause of COPD.

71
00:02:45.090 --> 00:02:47.119
In other countries, third world countries,

72
00:02:47.119 --> 00:02:49.179
it may be the burning of fossil fuels

73
00:02:49.179 --> 00:02:50.990
to cook or heat the home.

74
00:02:50.990 --> 00:02:51.963
And then of course,

75
00:02:51.963 --> 00:02:53.661
don't forget about occupational exposures,

76
00:02:53.661 --> 00:02:56.660
which we'll talk about later.

77
00:02:56.660 --> 00:02:58.261
The pathophysiology here.

78
00:02:58.261 --> 00:02:59.520
You inhale a bunch of things

79
00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:00.353
that irritate the lungs.

80
00:03:00.353 --> 00:03:01.771
The lungs are very sensitive.

81
00:03:01.771 --> 00:03:02.856
I don't like the lungs

82
00:03:02.856 --> 00:03:04.970
as a delivery system for anything,

83
00:03:04.970 --> 00:03:06.617
which is why we hate vaping.

84
00:03:06.617 --> 00:03:09.155
You know, the verdict is out on vaping,

85
00:03:09.155 --> 00:03:10.417
but I don't want patients

86
00:03:10.417 --> 00:03:13.882
breathing shit into their lungs.

87
00:03:13.882 --> 00:03:16.225
You know, the nicotine is not that harmful

88
00:03:16.225 --> 00:03:17.273
of a chemical.

89
00:03:17.273 --> 00:03:18.504
It's, it's all the other things

90
00:03:18.504 --> 00:03:19.923
that you're breathing in along,

91
00:03:19.923 --> 00:03:22.817
you know, the propylene glycol,

92
00:03:22.817 --> 00:03:24.023
which is one carbon chain

93
00:03:24.023 --> 00:03:25.591
removed from ethylene glycol,

94
00:03:25.591 --> 00:03:26.836
which is antifreeze.

95
00:03:26.836 --> 00:03:28.027
This keeps me up at night.

96
00:03:28.027 --> 00:03:28.860
Anyway.

97
00:03:28.860 --> 00:03:30.936
So patients are breathing things into their lungs

98
00:03:30.936 --> 00:03:31.772
like cigarette smoke.

99
00:03:31.772 --> 00:03:34.895
Causes irritation that results in inflammation.

100
00:03:34.895 --> 00:03:36.454
Eventually airflow limitation,

101
00:03:36.454 --> 00:03:38.787
which leads to the symptoms.

102
00:03:40.338 --> 00:03:42.034
Now, the hallmark symptoms of course,

103
00:03:42.034 --> 00:03:44.050
you know this, chronic cough,

104
00:03:44.050 --> 00:03:45.774
dyspnea and sputum production

105
00:03:45.774 --> 00:03:47.766
are the biggest ones.

106
00:03:47.766 --> 00:03:49.722
Pay attention to the last one on the left.

107
00:03:49.722 --> 00:03:50.951
Recurrent respiratory infection.

108
00:03:50.951 --> 00:03:52.720
Some of these patients with COPD

109
00:03:52.720 --> 00:03:54.207
may not think they have COPD.

110
00:03:54.207 --> 00:03:55.759
They might deny symptoms,

111
00:03:55.759 --> 00:03:57.469
but they're frequent flyers at your office

112
00:03:57.469 --> 00:04:00.996
or at urgent care with respiratory infections.

113
00:04:00.996 --> 00:04:02.548
Also on the right,

114
00:04:02.548 --> 00:04:04.785
weight loss is an independent risk factor

115
00:04:04.785 --> 00:04:05.952
for mortality.

116
00:04:06.853 --> 00:04:08.527
So with the work of breathing

117
00:04:08.527 --> 00:04:10.467
in your end stage patients,

118
00:04:10.467 --> 00:04:12.366
they will actually start losing weight,

119
00:04:12.366 --> 00:04:15.111
and that's a ominous sign.

120
00:04:15.111 --> 00:04:17.924
Now, when to think about COPD?

121
00:04:17.924 --> 00:04:18.866
Every smoker?

122
00:04:18.866 --> 00:04:19.699
No.

123
00:04:19.699 --> 00:04:20.839
The recommendation is,

124
00:04:20.839 --> 00:04:23.343
you wanna think of symptomatic smokers.

125
00:04:23.343 --> 00:04:25.424
The reason is because many patients

126
00:04:25.424 --> 00:04:27.371
with GOLD level two COPD

127
00:04:27.371 --> 00:04:29.531
don't complain of any symptoms at all.

128
00:04:29.531 --> 00:04:32.006
So you really wanna look at the symptoms.

129
00:04:32.006 --> 00:04:33.214
Again, remember,

130
00:04:33.214 --> 00:04:34.837
recurrent respiratory infections

131
00:04:34.837 --> 00:04:36.178
are something to consider.

132
00:04:36.178 --> 00:04:37.287
If you have a younger patient,

133
00:04:37.287 --> 00:04:40.291
you should do an Alpha-1 antitrypsin level.

134
00:04:40.291 --> 00:04:41.870
The World Health Organization

135
00:04:41.870 --> 00:04:44.369
has recently changed their recommendation,

136
00:04:44.369 --> 00:04:45.783
and they now recommend

137
00:04:45.783 --> 00:04:47.485
an Alpha-1 antitrypsin level

138
00:04:47.485 --> 00:04:50.318
on all COPD patients at diagnosis.

139
00:04:52.266 --> 00:04:53.099
What about

140
00:04:53.099 --> 00:04:54.635
screening high risk asymptomatic patients?

141
00:04:54.635 --> 00:04:55.761
Well, this patient has you know,

142
00:04:55.761 --> 00:04:58.688
a 50 pack year history of smoking.

143
00:04:58.688 --> 00:04:59.986
Shouldn't we screen them?

144
00:04:59.986 --> 00:05:02.736
Well, 2022 JAMA study showed that

145
00:05:03.814 --> 00:05:07.372
although screening does find disease,

146
00:05:07.372 --> 00:05:10.452
it doesn't change the outcome of the disease.

147
00:05:10.452 --> 00:05:11.832
So that's what's interesting here

148
00:05:11.832 --> 00:05:13.025
with COPD is,

149
00:05:13.025 --> 00:05:15.791
we're really concerned with the disease outcome.

150
00:05:15.791 --> 00:05:17.640
The best way to change

151
00:05:17.640 --> 00:05:19.742
the course of the illness

152
00:05:19.742 --> 00:05:21.884
is to get them to quit smoking.

153
00:05:21.884 --> 00:05:26.633
So the US Preventive Services Task Force in 2022

154
00:05:26.633 --> 00:05:28.498
told us that we should not be screening

155
00:05:28.498 --> 00:05:29.906
asymptomatic patients.

156
00:05:29.906 --> 00:05:31.001
So you wanna stick with

157
00:05:31.001 --> 00:05:33.444
screening your symptomatic smokers.

158
00:05:33.444 --> 00:05:34.612
Your differential here,

159
00:05:34.612 --> 00:05:35.593
think of anything that can cause

160
00:05:35.593 --> 00:05:37.077
dyspnea and sputum production.

161
00:05:37.077 --> 00:05:37.910
Cough.

162
00:05:37.910 --> 00:05:39.380
Asthma is probably the biggest one,

163
00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:40.789
tends to occur earlier in life,

164
00:05:40.789 --> 00:05:41.963
tends to be reversible

165
00:05:41.963 --> 00:05:44.503
that responds well to a bronchodilator.

166
00:05:44.503 --> 00:05:46.703
CHF is another big one.

167
00:05:46.703 --> 00:05:49.113
You know, same ages,

168
00:05:49.113 --> 00:05:51.351
you know, middle aged to older patients

169
00:05:51.351 --> 00:05:53.744
can have heart failure.

170
00:05:53.744 --> 00:05:55.189
Don't forget about tuberculosis.

171
00:05:55.189 --> 00:05:56.271
As David mentioned,

172
00:05:56.271 --> 00:05:59.299
they will ask you tuberculosis questions,

173
00:05:59.299 --> 00:06:01.049
plural on the boards.

174
00:06:02.132 --> 00:06:05.869
So we'll deal with that this afternoon as well.

175
00:06:05.869 --> 00:06:06.980
Other differentials,

176
00:06:06.980 --> 00:06:08.871
I like to think of intrathoracic

177
00:06:08.871 --> 00:06:10.152
or extrathoracic.

178
00:06:10.152 --> 00:06:11.411
Intrathoracic causes.

179
00:06:11.411 --> 00:06:13.041
Could be interstitial lung diseases

180
00:06:13.041 --> 00:06:14.451
like pulmonary fibrosis,

181
00:06:14.451 --> 00:06:16.765
cystic fibrosis, lung cancer.

182
00:06:16.765 --> 00:06:18.574
Don't forget about lung cancer.

183
00:06:18.574 --> 00:06:20.470
Extra thoracic.

184
00:06:20.470 --> 00:06:22.030
There's a lot of things that can cause

185
00:06:22.030 --> 00:06:23.279
chronic cough.

186
00:06:23.279 --> 00:06:24.532
Chronic cough can come from

187
00:06:24.532 --> 00:06:26.668
the lung parenchyma itself.

188
00:06:26.668 --> 00:06:29.194
It can come from sinus drainage down.

189
00:06:29.194 --> 00:06:30.037
That's very common.

190
00:06:30.037 --> 00:06:31.737
That tends to be the throat clearing.

191
00:06:31.737 --> 00:06:32.873
(throat coughing)

192
00:06:32.873 --> 00:06:34.502
That kind of thing that your patients will do.

193
00:06:34.502 --> 00:06:37.404
Or it could come from gastroesophageal reflux up.

194
00:06:37.404 --> 00:06:40.841
And then medication effects like ACE inhibitors.

195
00:06:40.841 --> 00:06:41.914
Imaging studies.

196
00:06:41.914 --> 00:06:43.226
You're probably gonna do a chest x-ray

197
00:06:43.226 --> 00:06:44.306
or a CT on these patients.

198
00:06:44.306 --> 00:06:46.123
Helpful to exclude other causes.

199
00:06:46.123 --> 00:06:47.534
Don't forget about ABGs

200
00:06:47.534 --> 00:06:49.784
to see if they need oxygen.

201
00:06:51.770 --> 00:06:53.235
Okay, first question.

202
00:06:53.235 --> 00:06:55.490
We have a 52-year-old patient.

203
00:06:55.490 --> 00:06:56.918
Hold on.

204
00:06:56.918 --> 00:06:59.001
Now, I said 52-year-old patient.

205
00:06:59.001 --> 00:07:01.418
I did not say black or white.

206
00:07:03.182 --> 00:07:05.492
I did not say male or female.

207
00:07:05.492 --> 00:07:08.659
The evolving trend and board questions

208
00:07:09.734 --> 00:07:13.734
is to not specify race or sex unless it matters.

209
00:07:16.389 --> 00:07:17.617
It's an evolving trend.

210
00:07:17.617 --> 00:07:18.959
So we're not fully there yet.

211
00:07:18.959 --> 00:07:20.628
There's a huge bank of questions.

212
00:07:20.628 --> 00:07:22.729
Some of these are old, some of them are new.

213
00:07:22.729 --> 00:07:24.459
Not all test writers, you know,

214
00:07:24.459 --> 00:07:25.735
adhere to this formula.

215
00:07:25.735 --> 00:07:27.957
But the new evolving trend with test questions

216
00:07:27.957 --> 00:07:31.502
is to not mention the sex of the patient

217
00:07:31.502 --> 00:07:34.344
or the race of the patient unless it matters.

218
00:07:34.344 --> 00:07:37.646
So in my questions, you won't see it,

219
00:07:37.646 --> 00:07:40.300
but if you do pay attention.

220
00:07:40.300 --> 00:07:41.133
All right.

221
00:07:41.133 --> 00:07:42.134
So we have a 52-year-old patient

222
00:07:42.134 --> 00:07:44.493
presents with progressive cough, wheezing,

223
00:07:44.493 --> 00:07:46.063
and occasional sputum production

224
00:07:46.063 --> 00:07:48.027
over the past few years.

225
00:07:48.027 --> 00:07:50.176
They, not he or she.

226
00:07:50.176 --> 00:07:52.472
We're trying to be general gender neutral today,

227
00:07:52.472 --> 00:07:53.305
right.

228
00:07:53.305 --> 00:07:54.388
This is 2024.

229
00:07:55.224 --> 00:07:57.378
They have smoked one pack of cigarettes per day

230
00:07:57.378 --> 00:07:58.211
for 20 years,

231
00:07:58.211 --> 00:07:59.888
and their symptoms have worsened lately

232
00:07:59.888 --> 00:08:01.386
so that they often feel

233
00:08:01.386 --> 00:08:04.805
too short of breath to play with their grandkids.

234
00:08:04.805 --> 00:08:06.953
Which one of the following spirometry results

235
00:08:06.953 --> 00:08:08.463
would be consistent with the diagnosis

236
00:08:08.463 --> 00:08:10.253
of moderate COPD?

237
00:08:10.253 --> 00:08:14.170
A, an FEV 1 over FC ratio greater than 70%

238
00:08:15.129 --> 00:08:19.728
with an FEV 1 greater than 80% predicted.

239
00:08:19.728 --> 00:08:23.038
There's a lot going on with these number slides.

240
00:08:23.038 --> 00:08:25.892
Two, the ratio less than 70%

241
00:08:25.892 --> 00:08:28.550
with an FEV 1 between 50 and 80.

242
00:08:28.550 --> 00:08:31.383
C, the ratio greater than 70%

243
00:08:32.431 --> 00:08:34.807
with the same ratio,

244
00:08:34.807 --> 00:08:38.050
the same percentage of FEV 1, 50 to 80.

245
00:08:38.050 --> 00:08:40.438
Or D, the lower ratio

246
00:08:40.438 --> 00:08:43.163
with the lower predicted percentage.

247
00:08:43.163 --> 00:08:45.857
So if you didn't memorize this,

248
00:08:45.857 --> 00:08:48.767
sometimes if you're lucky, you can sleuth it out.

249
00:08:48.767 --> 00:08:50.195
So it asked

250
00:08:50.195 --> 00:08:52.755
what the diagnosis of moderate COPD was.

251
00:08:52.755 --> 00:08:55.083
It didn't ask for mild, it didn't ask for severe.

252
00:08:55.083 --> 00:08:56.804
So I'm probably gonna go with B or C

253
00:08:56.804 --> 00:08:58.189
if I don't know anything,

254
00:08:58.189 --> 00:09:01.049
just because those are the middle numbers, right.

255
00:09:01.049 --> 00:09:03.334
But if you look a little deeper,

256
00:09:03.334 --> 00:09:06.167
B and D both have the lower ratio,

257
00:09:09.630 --> 00:09:11.976
and B and C both have

258
00:09:11.976 --> 00:09:15.295
the same predictive percentage.

259
00:09:15.295 --> 00:09:16.795
If I knew nothing,

260
00:09:17.997 --> 00:09:19.496
I would do the intersection of those two,

261
00:09:19.496 --> 00:09:21.329
which happens to be B.

262
00:09:27.219 --> 00:09:28.101
My goodness.

263
00:09:28.101 --> 00:09:29.679
It happens to be the right answer.

264
00:09:29.679 --> 00:09:31.293
So sometimes you can get lucky with these.

265
00:09:31.293 --> 00:09:32.735
Good job, everybody.

266
00:09:32.735 --> 00:09:33.568
Okay.

267
00:09:33.568 --> 00:09:35.452
So our strategy for assessing COPD,

268
00:09:35.452 --> 00:09:36.914
we're gonna look at four things.

269
00:09:36.914 --> 00:09:39.279
Airflow limitation looking at with spirometry.

270
00:09:39.279 --> 00:09:40.577
We're gonna look at symptoms.

271
00:09:40.577 --> 00:09:43.331
Risk of exacerbation and comorbidities.

272
00:09:43.331 --> 00:09:44.631
These are all important.

273
00:09:44.631 --> 00:09:46.811
So spirometry is the key test

274
00:09:46.811 --> 00:09:49.781
for diagnosing obstructive illnesses,

275
00:09:49.781 --> 00:09:52.193
including COPD and asthma.

276
00:09:52.193 --> 00:09:54.312
What we're looking at is the FEV 1.

277
00:09:54.312 --> 00:09:55.973
That's the amount of air they can get out

278
00:09:55.973 --> 00:09:56.908
in the first second.

279
00:09:56.908 --> 00:09:58.414
With an obstruction,

280
00:09:58.414 --> 00:10:00.509
it's kind of like breathing through a straw.

281
00:10:00.509 --> 00:10:02.495
(air huffing)

282
00:10:02.495 --> 00:10:05.264
It's gonna take a long time to get that air out.

283
00:10:05.264 --> 00:10:07.212
So your forced expiratory volume

284
00:10:07.212 --> 00:10:08.434
in the first second

285
00:10:08.434 --> 00:10:10.934
is going to be delayed, right.

286
00:10:11.848 --> 00:10:13.343
And then that ratio over

287
00:10:13.343 --> 00:10:14.803
the forced vital capacity,

288
00:10:14.803 --> 00:10:18.286
the amount of error you can get out in total

289
00:10:18.286 --> 00:10:21.078
should be less than 70%,

290
00:10:21.078 --> 00:10:24.260
and that confirms the diagnosis of COPD.

291
00:10:24.260 --> 00:10:28.379
Try to memorize that percentage for the boards.

292
00:10:28.379 --> 00:10:30.320
Now here's an example of a flow volume loop.

293
00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:32.413
On the bottom we have the inspiration,

294
00:10:32.413 --> 00:10:33.812
which is a nice curve.

295
00:10:33.812 --> 00:10:36.224
And then we have the expiration on the top.

296
00:10:36.224 --> 00:10:38.793
You've got the peak expiratory flow

297
00:10:38.793 --> 00:10:40.500
is your highest number,

298
00:10:40.500 --> 00:10:42.275
and then the amount you can get out in a second,

299
00:10:42.275 --> 00:10:44.866
and then down from there.

300
00:10:44.866 --> 00:10:48.246
Now here is a volume over time curve.

301
00:10:48.246 --> 00:10:49.373
Again, pay attention

302
00:10:49.373 --> 00:10:51.591
to the forced expiratory volume

303
00:10:51.591 --> 00:10:53.119
in the first second.

304
00:10:53.119 --> 00:10:54.133
Normal patients,

305
00:10:54.133 --> 00:10:55.657
they can get it out pretty quickly.

306
00:10:55.657 --> 00:10:58.423
Asthmatics and COPD, it takes a lot longer.

307
00:10:58.423 --> 00:11:00.724
Asthmatics can eventually get all the air out,

308
00:11:00.724 --> 00:11:03.673
but COPD patients usually, you know,

309
00:11:03.673 --> 00:11:05.033
do have some decreased

310
00:11:05.033 --> 00:11:07.616
in their forced vital capacity.

311
00:11:10.289 --> 00:11:11.122
Okay.

312
00:11:11.122 --> 00:11:12.891
When not to do spirometry?

313
00:11:12.891 --> 00:11:15.205
Well, some of these are pretty common sense,

314
00:11:15.205 --> 00:11:16.786
but they could pop up on the boards.

315
00:11:16.786 --> 00:11:17.765
You're not gonna do it

316
00:11:17.765 --> 00:11:19.769
if a patient's hemodynamically unstable.

317
00:11:19.769 --> 00:11:22.192
If they've had a you know, very recent MI.

318
00:11:22.192 --> 00:11:25.612
If they've got a infection, a pneumothorax.

319
00:11:25.612 --> 00:11:26.833
If they've got an aneurysm

320
00:11:26.833 --> 00:11:29.079
of the abdominal aorta.

321
00:11:29.079 --> 00:11:31.201
Intracranial hypertension or retinal detachments.

322
00:11:31.201 --> 00:11:33.347
Those would be absolute contraindications.

323
00:11:33.347 --> 00:11:34.797
Relative contraindications.

324
00:11:34.797 --> 00:11:36.953
Children, anyone under five

325
00:11:36.953 --> 00:11:39.244
isn't gonna sit still in order to go through

326
00:11:39.244 --> 00:11:41.577
the spirometry and so forth.

327
00:11:43.958 --> 00:11:47.541
Now, let's go back a couple slides to that.

328
00:11:48.447 --> 00:11:51.243
Look at that in inspiratory curve.

329
00:11:51.243 --> 00:11:53.779
That inspiratory curve should look that way.

330
00:11:53.779 --> 00:11:56.441
If it's flat, then that need,

331
00:11:56.441 --> 00:11:57.324
that means that there's

332
00:11:57.324 --> 00:11:59.625
an upper airway obstruction,

333
00:11:59.625 --> 00:12:01.716
and then you want to send the patient

334
00:12:01.716 --> 00:12:03.705
off for nasopharyngoscopy.

335
00:12:03.705 --> 00:12:05.240
I was asked that question

336
00:12:05.240 --> 00:12:06.725
on the boards last time.

337
00:12:06.725 --> 00:12:07.837
It annoyed me

338
00:12:07.837 --> 00:12:09.408
because I've never seen it in practice,

339
00:12:09.408 --> 00:12:10.307
but that's why I've included

340
00:12:10.307 --> 00:12:12.115
the information here for y'all.

341
00:12:12.115 --> 00:12:12.965
So think of that.

342
00:12:12.965 --> 00:12:15.476
If you see a flattened inspiratory loop,

343
00:12:15.476 --> 00:12:18.724
nasal obstruction and nasopharyngoscopy.

344
00:12:18.724 --> 00:12:21.156
These are in between diagnoses

345
00:12:21.156 --> 00:12:22.486
that they won't ask you on the board

346
00:12:22.486 --> 00:12:24.069
Pre-COPD and PRISm.

347
00:12:25.227 --> 00:12:27.310
Now what hasn't changed

348
00:12:27.310 --> 00:12:30.584
is the classification strategy for COPD.

349
00:12:30.584 --> 00:12:33.141
So we have Gold 1, 2, 3, and 4.

350
00:12:33.141 --> 00:12:34.462
We typically call them mild, moderate,

351
00:12:34.462 --> 00:12:36.484
severe or very severe.

352
00:12:36.484 --> 00:12:39.213
Or I prefer the term end stage.

353
00:12:39.213 --> 00:12:42.702
And this is with our ratio less than 70%.

354
00:12:42.702 --> 00:12:45.512
If we have greater than 80% predicted

355
00:12:45.512 --> 00:12:47.718
on FEV 1, that's mild.

356
00:12:47.718 --> 00:12:50.396
Less than 80% is moderate.

357
00:12:50.396 --> 00:12:52.498
Less than 50% is severe,

358
00:12:52.498 --> 00:12:55.495
and less than 30% is end stage.

359
00:12:55.495 --> 00:12:57.412
So greater than 80, less than 80.

360
00:12:57.412 --> 00:12:59.327
Less than 50, less than 30.

361
00:12:59.327 --> 00:13:03.410
Those are the ways to remember these GOLD levels.

362
00:13:04.625 --> 00:13:07.728
Now this was another one of these questions

363
00:13:07.728 --> 00:13:10.399
that popped up on the boards that annoyed me.

364
00:13:10.399 --> 00:13:11.977
If you are a radiologist

365
00:13:11.977 --> 00:13:13.449
or if you're into research,

366
00:13:13.449 --> 00:13:14.450
there are different

367
00:13:14.450 --> 00:13:18.367
morphologic emphysematous subtypes on CT scans.

368
00:13:20.957 --> 00:13:21.790
Who knew?

369
00:13:23.094 --> 00:13:25.163
Well here's what they are.

370
00:13:25.163 --> 00:13:28.202
If you see central lobar emphysema,

371
00:13:28.202 --> 00:13:29.822
that's classically associated

372
00:13:29.822 --> 00:13:31.635
with smoking-induced COPD.

373
00:13:31.635 --> 00:13:34.216
If you see pan lobular emphysema,

374
00:13:34.216 --> 00:13:35.807
that's classically associated

375
00:13:35.807 --> 00:13:38.868
with homozygous alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency.

376
00:13:38.868 --> 00:13:41.879
I was asked that question on the boards.

377
00:13:41.879 --> 00:13:43.478
For me in private practice,

378
00:13:43.478 --> 00:13:44.769
it's not very relevant.

379
00:13:44.769 --> 00:13:46.519
But here you have it.

380
00:13:47.698 --> 00:13:49.238
Next question.

381
00:13:49.238 --> 00:13:50.470
Due to the weak correlation

382
00:13:50.470 --> 00:13:52.670
between the severity of airflow limitation,

383
00:13:52.670 --> 00:13:54.804
and the symptoms experienced

384
00:13:54.804 --> 00:13:56.954
by most patients with COPD,

385
00:13:56.954 --> 00:13:59.031
which one of the following should be obtained

386
00:13:59.031 --> 00:13:59.964
at each office visit?

387
00:13:59.964 --> 00:14:02.168
A, a chest radiograph.

388
00:14:02.168 --> 00:14:05.236
B, laboratory assessment including CBC,

389
00:14:05.236 --> 00:14:07.805
C-reactive protein and procalcitonin.

390
00:14:07.805 --> 00:14:08.972
C, spirometry.

391
00:14:09.815 --> 00:14:13.898
Or D, a validated multidimensional questionnaire.

392
00:14:18.519 --> 00:14:19.535
Good.

393
00:14:19.535 --> 00:14:21.514
Validated multidimensional questionnaires

394
00:14:21.514 --> 00:14:23.932
is always the right answer on the boards.

395
00:14:23.932 --> 00:14:26.253
They love these questionnaires.

396
00:14:26.253 --> 00:14:28.784
So this is assessing the symptoms.

397
00:14:28.784 --> 00:14:30.318
These are highly variable.

398
00:14:30.318 --> 00:14:31.602
Like I said, many patients don't complain

399
00:14:31.602 --> 00:14:32.763
of any symptoms at all

400
00:14:32.763 --> 00:14:33.925
till you start getting into

401
00:14:33.925 --> 00:14:34.898
the nitty gritty here.

402
00:14:34.898 --> 00:14:36.886
The best one is the COPD Assessment

403
00:14:36.886 --> 00:14:39.795
or CAT test, which is multidimensional,

404
00:14:39.795 --> 00:14:41.381
followed by the mMRC,

405
00:14:41.381 --> 00:14:44.390
which is more symptom based.

406
00:14:44.390 --> 00:14:46.776
There's a link to it if you wanna look at it.

407
00:14:46.776 --> 00:14:47.728
There's what it looks like.

408
00:14:47.728 --> 00:14:48.566
You add 'em up.

409
00:14:48.566 --> 00:14:50.384
Higher is worse.

410
00:14:50.384 --> 00:14:51.929
Anything above 15 is bad.

411
00:14:51.929 --> 00:14:52.762
Okay.

412
00:14:52.762 --> 00:14:54.879
The risk of exacerbations is next.

413
00:14:54.879 --> 00:14:57.009
The best predictor of future behavior

414
00:14:57.009 --> 00:14:59.009
is past behavior, right.

415
00:15:00.129 --> 00:15:02.039
So that's how we predict risk.

416
00:15:02.039 --> 00:15:03.868
If they've had two or more exacerbations

417
00:15:03.868 --> 00:15:04.899
within the last year,

418
00:15:04.899 --> 00:15:06.077
they're at high risk or if they've had

419
00:15:06.077 --> 00:15:08.697
one or more hospitalizations for their COPD.

420
00:15:08.697 --> 00:15:09.900
Next is comorbidities.

421
00:15:09.900 --> 00:15:12.599
These are very important and very common.

422
00:15:12.599 --> 00:15:14.916
They can worsen the diagnosis

423
00:15:14.916 --> 00:15:18.462
for either illness when they occur concomitantly.

424
00:15:18.462 --> 00:15:20.470
Cardiovascular diseases are very high,

425
00:15:20.470 --> 00:15:22.372
especially atrial fibrillation,

426
00:15:22.372 --> 00:15:25.205
which goes hand in hand with COPD.

427
00:15:26.200 --> 00:15:27.834
Don't forget about lung cancer.

428
00:15:27.834 --> 00:15:30.824
Sleep apnea is a big one as well as GERD,

429
00:15:30.824 --> 00:15:32.666
which confers an independent risk factor

430
00:15:32.666 --> 00:15:34.166
for exacerbations.

431
00:15:35.114 --> 00:15:36.375
How you manage these,

432
00:15:36.375 --> 00:15:37.935
you're not going to do anything differently.

433
00:15:37.935 --> 00:15:39.947
You're gonna manage them the same,

434
00:15:39.947 --> 00:15:42.252
but it's very important that they be recognized.

435
00:15:42.252 --> 00:15:44.257
For example, patient comes in

436
00:15:44.257 --> 00:15:45.090
with COPD and their,

437
00:15:45.090 --> 00:15:46.860
"Doc ,"I'm short of breath."

438
00:15:46.860 --> 00:15:48.733
Well, is it the COPD?

439
00:15:48.733 --> 00:15:52.241
Maybe it's heart failure, cardiovascular disease.

440
00:15:52.241 --> 00:15:54.155
"Doc, I've got this worsening cough.

441
00:15:54.155 --> 00:15:55.316
Is it my COPD?"

442
00:15:55.316 --> 00:15:56.149
I don't know.

443
00:15:56.149 --> 00:15:58.376
Could it be gastroesophageal reflux disease?

444
00:15:58.376 --> 00:15:59.941
"I'm fatigued."

445
00:15:59.941 --> 00:16:00.991
Is that COPD?

446
00:16:00.991 --> 00:16:01.931
Could it be depression?

447
00:16:01.931 --> 00:16:03.334
So these are the things you need to look for

448
00:16:03.334 --> 00:16:05.452
as clinicians with these comorbidities.

449
00:16:05.452 --> 00:16:08.121
And then there's the Global Assessment Tool.

450
00:16:08.121 --> 00:16:09.952
It used to be the ABCD.

451
00:16:09.952 --> 00:16:10.785
It's the ABE.

452
00:16:10.785 --> 00:16:11.797
How many of are you familiar with

453
00:16:11.797 --> 00:16:13.540
the the Global Tool?

454
00:16:13.540 --> 00:16:14.880
We'll get to it.

455
00:16:14.880 --> 00:16:16.035
I'll show it to you

456
00:16:16.035 --> 00:16:19.202
when we get into the management areas.

457
00:16:20.285 --> 00:16:21.933
Okay.

458
00:16:21.933 --> 00:16:24.682
The goal here with COPD is to

459
00:16:24.682 --> 00:16:27.859
reduce the symptoms and reduce the risk, right.

460
00:16:27.859 --> 00:16:29.784
The best way to do that

461
00:16:29.784 --> 00:16:31.732
is to get them to quit smoking.

462
00:16:31.732 --> 00:16:33.250
So this has the greatest capacity

463
00:16:33.250 --> 00:16:36.586
to influence the history of the disease.

464
00:16:36.586 --> 00:16:39.290
It's important to remember

465
00:16:39.290 --> 00:16:40.991
that nothing prolongs the life

466
00:16:40.991 --> 00:16:42.593
of a patient with COPD,

467
00:16:42.593 --> 00:16:45.246
which this is really all symptomatic management.

468
00:16:45.246 --> 00:16:46.753
The only thing that can prolong their life

469
00:16:46.753 --> 00:16:48.916
is removing the environmental insult,

470
00:16:48.916 --> 00:16:52.005
which is usually cigarette smoking.

471
00:16:52.005 --> 00:16:54.071
Okay, next question.

472
00:16:54.071 --> 00:16:56.431
So what I like to do

473
00:16:56.431 --> 00:17:00.113
when I present is I give you one case,

474
00:17:00.113 --> 00:17:01.905
and we follow that same patient

475
00:17:01.905 --> 00:17:03.353
through the illness.

476
00:17:03.353 --> 00:17:06.273
So this is still our 52-year-old patient.

477
00:17:06.273 --> 00:17:09.006
So your patient with GOLD stage two COPD

478
00:17:09.006 --> 00:17:10.445
comes in for a routine visit.

479
00:17:10.445 --> 00:17:12.052
They had been controlled

480
00:17:12.052 --> 00:17:14.801
on a LABA/LAMA combination inhaler,

481
00:17:14.801 --> 00:17:16.099
but for the past several months

482
00:17:16.099 --> 00:17:17.574
they have been complaining

483
00:17:17.574 --> 00:17:19.734
of increased breathing difficulty,

484
00:17:19.734 --> 00:17:21.006
and sputum production

485
00:17:21.006 --> 00:17:23.216
requiring one visit at Urgent Care.

486
00:17:23.216 --> 00:17:25.198
They deny chest pain or fever.

487
00:17:25.198 --> 00:17:26.759
When considering adding

488
00:17:26.759 --> 00:17:28.239
an inhaled corticosteroid,

489
00:17:28.239 --> 00:17:30.595
which test would be most helpful to order?

490
00:17:30.595 --> 00:17:32.928
A, a blood eosinophil count.

491
00:17:33.937 --> 00:17:36.314
B, a chest radiograph.

492
00:17:36.314 --> 00:17:38.117
C, C-reactive protein.

493
00:17:38.117 --> 00:17:40.284
Or D, procalcitonin level.

494
00:17:45.126 --> 00:17:45.959
Good.

495
00:17:45.959 --> 00:17:46.792
Blood eosinophil count.

496
00:17:46.792 --> 00:17:47.885
Y'all are gonna do great

497
00:17:47.885 --> 00:17:49.633
on the boards because this is new stuff.

498
00:17:49.633 --> 00:17:50.844
Good for you.

499
00:17:50.844 --> 00:17:51.677
All right.

500
00:17:51.677 --> 00:17:53.696
So let's get into management.

501
00:17:53.696 --> 00:17:57.025
Beta agonist first line therapy in mild patients

502
00:17:57.025 --> 00:17:58.536
at low risk.

503
00:17:58.536 --> 00:18:00.662
Long-acting bronchodilators

504
00:18:00.662 --> 00:18:02.958
are generally preferred over short-acting.

505
00:18:02.958 --> 00:18:05.291
Keep in mind that in asthma,

506
00:18:06.464 --> 00:18:09.512
monotherapy with a long-acting beta-agonist

507
00:18:09.512 --> 00:18:10.937
is out

508
00:18:10.937 --> 00:18:14.476
because it worsens cardiovascular mortality.

509
00:18:14.476 --> 00:18:16.685
Long-acting beta-agonist monotherapy,

510
00:18:16.685 --> 00:18:18.517
and asthma out,

511
00:18:18.517 --> 00:18:22.569
but it doesn't cause a problem in COPD.

512
00:18:22.569 --> 00:18:24.461
So you are allowed to use monotherapy

513
00:18:24.461 --> 00:18:26.801
with a LABA in COPD,

514
00:18:26.801 --> 00:18:28.008
but the evolving trend

515
00:18:28.008 --> 00:18:30.974
is really combination therapy.

516
00:18:30.974 --> 00:18:32.125
Antimuscarinic.

517
00:18:32.125 --> 00:18:33.683
Long-acting muscarinic antagonist.

518
00:18:33.683 --> 00:18:37.761
These are your preferred starting medications.

519
00:18:37.761 --> 00:18:41.738
Host of benefits with minimal side effects.

520
00:18:41.738 --> 00:18:43.929
Combination therapy has the best results.

521
00:18:43.929 --> 00:18:45.520
We've got tons of these inhalers,

522
00:18:45.520 --> 00:18:47.437
which one is up to you.

523
00:18:48.597 --> 00:18:50.886
Inhaled corticosteroids.

524
00:18:50.886 --> 00:18:52.646
More of a benefit in asthma.

525
00:18:52.646 --> 00:18:54.359
But if you have a patient with you know,

526
00:18:54.359 --> 00:18:56.414
recurrent exacerbations,

527
00:18:56.414 --> 00:18:58.161
a lot of sputum production,

528
00:18:58.161 --> 00:19:00.857
you might want to consider

529
00:19:00.857 --> 00:19:02.554
adding an inhaled corticosteroid

530
00:19:02.554 --> 00:19:05.307
if they are at GOLD stages two to four.

531
00:19:05.307 --> 00:19:06.957
The best way to determine it

532
00:19:06.957 --> 00:19:09.548
is we have this objective measurement

533
00:19:09.548 --> 00:19:11.406
called a CBC.

534
00:19:11.406 --> 00:19:13.556
And there's a blood eosinophil count on there.

535
00:19:13.556 --> 00:19:15.451
So if you see an eosinophil count

536
00:19:15.451 --> 00:19:17.111
greater than 300,

537
00:19:17.111 --> 00:19:19.241
they are more likely to benefit from an inhaled

538
00:19:19.241 --> 00:19:21.651
corticosteroid or if they have asthma of course,

539
00:19:21.651 --> 00:19:23.792
and that's the COPD overlap syndrome.

540
00:19:23.792 --> 00:19:26.111
So here's your slide to help you.

541
00:19:26.111 --> 00:19:27.113
Should we put 'em on

542
00:19:27.113 --> 00:19:28.361
an inhaled corticosteroid?

543
00:19:28.361 --> 00:19:30.143
If they've had frequent hospitalizations,

544
00:19:30.143 --> 00:19:32.160
exacerbations, or a high blood eosinophil count.

545
00:19:32.160 --> 00:19:33.121
Yes.

546
00:19:33.121 --> 00:19:34.523
If it's in the middle maybe,

547
00:19:34.523 --> 00:19:36.255
and if it's not

548
00:19:36.255 --> 00:19:37.993
or if they've had repeated pneumonia,

549
00:19:37.993 --> 00:19:38.993
probably no.

550
00:19:40.595 --> 00:19:43.355
So that's a helpful slide.

551
00:19:43.355 --> 00:19:46.182
Oral glucocorticoids, yes for exacerbations,

552
00:19:46.182 --> 00:19:47.842
but not for routine management.

553
00:19:47.842 --> 00:19:50.521
PDE-4 inhibitors like Roflumilast, yes

554
00:19:50.521 --> 00:19:53.282
for GOLD stages three or four.

555
00:19:53.282 --> 00:19:55.782
Daily or biweekly Azithromycin

556
00:19:56.871 --> 00:19:59.234
has been shown to reduce exacerbations

557
00:19:59.234 --> 00:20:00.894
in those that get frequent infections,

558
00:20:00.894 --> 00:20:03.164
but it can come with a cost.

559
00:20:03.164 --> 00:20:05.553
Don't forget about your inhaler delivery system.

560
00:20:05.553 --> 00:20:07.396
The metered dose inhaler is you know,

561
00:20:07.396 --> 00:20:08.374
the most commonly used,

562
00:20:08.374 --> 00:20:10.252
but you've gotta have the coordination

563
00:20:10.252 --> 00:20:11.332
to use it, right,

564
00:20:11.332 --> 00:20:12.766
which some elderly patients

565
00:20:12.766 --> 00:20:15.768
or younger patients might struggle with.

566
00:20:15.768 --> 00:20:18.962
The dry powder inhaler is breath activated.

567
00:20:18.962 --> 00:20:20.215
So you don't have to worry about

568
00:20:20.215 --> 00:20:22.015
the coordination,

569
00:20:22.015 --> 00:20:23.177
but you gotta be able to take

570
00:20:23.177 --> 00:20:24.355
a big strong breath.

571
00:20:24.355 --> 00:20:26.868
So keep that one in mind.

572
00:20:26.868 --> 00:20:27.984
The nebulizers are great

573
00:20:27.984 --> 00:20:29.984
but expensive and require electricity.

574
00:20:29.984 --> 00:20:31.516
You got the tubing maintenance to deal with.

575
00:20:31.516 --> 00:20:33.208
The soft mist inhalers are really nice.

576
00:20:33.208 --> 00:20:35.188
They're kinda the best of the both world.

577
00:20:35.188 --> 00:20:37.023
Really elegant,

578
00:20:37.023 --> 00:20:38.266
but they're a little bit more expensive,

579
00:20:38.266 --> 00:20:41.885
and they do come with a shelf life.

580
00:20:41.885 --> 00:20:43.255
Pulmonary rehabilitation.

581
00:20:43.255 --> 00:20:46.374
This is a multidimensional approach here.

582
00:20:46.374 --> 00:20:48.898
Please say to pulmonary rehab

583
00:20:48.898 --> 00:20:51.756
at any stage of COPD if you are asked

584
00:20:51.756 --> 00:20:54.089
that question on the boards.

585
00:20:55.155 --> 00:20:56.525
What about oxygen?

586
00:20:56.525 --> 00:20:58.299
Many of these patients require oxygen.

587
00:20:58.299 --> 00:21:00.943
So here's the information

588
00:21:00.943 --> 00:21:03.409
for when to prescribe supplemental oxygen.

589
00:21:03.409 --> 00:21:05.895
It's indicated for resting PAO2,

590
00:21:05.895 --> 00:21:07.895
less than 55 or 55 to 60

591
00:21:09.225 --> 00:21:11.064
if they have heart failure.

592
00:21:11.064 --> 00:21:13.897
Or a O2 SAT of less than 88%.

593
00:21:15.278 --> 00:21:16.856
Put 'em on oxygen,

594
00:21:16.856 --> 00:21:19.020
titrate up to greater than 90,

595
00:21:19.020 --> 00:21:21.668
have 'em come back for follow up.

596
00:21:21.668 --> 00:21:23.136
In a couple months,

597
00:21:23.136 --> 00:21:24.936
see how they're doing if they need to stay on it

598
00:21:24.936 --> 00:21:27.353
or if they find it effective.

599
00:21:29.519 --> 00:21:31.728
Palliative care with opioids,

600
00:21:31.728 --> 00:21:33.215
neuromuscular stimulation,

601
00:21:33.215 --> 00:21:34.657
oxygen, even fans blowing air

602
00:21:34.657 --> 00:21:36.783
onto the patient's face at night

603
00:21:36.783 --> 00:21:38.649
have all been found to be helpful.

604
00:21:38.649 --> 00:21:40.900
Ventilatory support if needed,

605
00:21:40.900 --> 00:21:42.529
and surgical interventions

606
00:21:42.529 --> 00:21:44.128
for your more severe patients

607
00:21:44.128 --> 00:21:47.545
with like your extreme bullets emphysema.

608
00:21:48.693 --> 00:21:49.526
Okay.

609
00:21:49.526 --> 00:21:53.380
Here's that ABE combined assessment tool.

610
00:21:53.380 --> 00:21:54.416
Here's what it looks like.

611
00:21:54.416 --> 00:21:56.611
So it used to be ABCD,

612
00:21:56.611 --> 00:21:58.023
it used to include the levels,

613
00:21:58.023 --> 00:21:59.054
they keep changing it.

614
00:21:59.054 --> 00:22:02.186
The newer iteration is the ABE tool.

615
00:22:02.186 --> 00:22:05.103
So on the X axis, we have symptoms.

616
00:22:06.430 --> 00:22:08.716
Fewer symptoms on the left,

617
00:22:08.716 --> 00:22:10.678
greater symptoms on the right.

618
00:22:10.678 --> 00:22:14.675
On the Y axis we have risk of exacerbations,

619
00:22:14.675 --> 00:22:18.152
Lower risk down, higher risk up.

620
00:22:18.152 --> 00:22:22.364
So your group a fewer symptoms, lower risk.

621
00:22:22.364 --> 00:22:25.150
Put 'em on a once a day bronchodilator,

622
00:22:25.150 --> 00:22:27.837
like a long-acting, you know,

623
00:22:27.837 --> 00:22:31.456
beta agonist or muscarinic antagonist.

624
00:22:31.456 --> 00:22:33.467
Group B, they're more symptomatic.

625
00:22:33.467 --> 00:22:36.757
So these patients have a COPD Assessment Test

626
00:22:36.757 --> 00:22:38.327
greater than 10.

627
00:22:38.327 --> 00:22:39.565
So those patients,

628
00:22:39.565 --> 00:22:41.033
when you see them in the office,

629
00:22:41.033 --> 00:22:42.437
and you give them that validated

630
00:22:42.437 --> 00:22:44.666
multidimensional questionnaire,

631
00:22:44.666 --> 00:22:46.442
you fill it out, add up the numbers.

632
00:22:46.442 --> 00:22:47.275
Oh look, you know

633
00:22:47.275 --> 00:22:48.991
"Mrs. Smith is at a 12."

634
00:22:48.991 --> 00:22:50.616
So she's got more symptoms.

635
00:22:50.616 --> 00:22:52.293
So now she needs a combination inhaler.

636
00:22:52.293 --> 00:22:53.789
LABA/LAMA.

637
00:22:53.789 --> 00:22:56.253
Higher risk patients

638
00:22:56.253 --> 00:22:59.170
need the combination bronchodilator

639
00:23:00.642 --> 00:23:04.590
plus or minus the inhaled corticosteroid

640
00:23:04.590 --> 00:23:07.853
if they have a blood eosinophil count above what?

641
00:23:07.853 --> 00:23:08.686
300.

642
00:23:08.686 --> 00:23:09.519
Good.

643
00:23:09.519 --> 00:23:10.478
Good, good, good, good, good.

644
00:23:10.478 --> 00:23:14.513
So this is your combined assessment tool.

645
00:23:14.513 --> 00:23:16.185
Now your management, what do you do?

646
00:23:16.185 --> 00:23:17.521
Mrs. Smith comes back in you know,

647
00:23:17.521 --> 00:23:18.496
a month later she's like,

648
00:23:18.496 --> 00:23:19.956
"You know, I'm still having dyspnea.

649
00:23:19.956 --> 00:23:20.913
Well, what are you on?"

650
00:23:20.913 --> 00:23:23.120
So you're gonna add another inhaler.

651
00:23:23.120 --> 00:23:25.692
She's not on a long-acting muscarinic antagonist.

652
00:23:25.692 --> 00:23:26.660
She needs to be on it.

653
00:23:26.660 --> 00:23:29.503
Don't forget about other comorbid illnesses

654
00:23:29.503 --> 00:23:31.120
that could be at play.

655
00:23:31.120 --> 00:23:33.363
Patient who has exacerbations

656
00:23:33.363 --> 00:23:35.330
probably needs to be on a steroid,

657
00:23:35.330 --> 00:23:38.541
but of course you may consider Roflumilast

658
00:23:38.541 --> 00:23:42.070
or weekly azithromycin in those cases.

659
00:23:42.070 --> 00:23:44.030
Always remember to assess

660
00:23:44.030 --> 00:23:45.928
their inhaler technique.

661
00:23:45.928 --> 00:23:48.186
This is big with COPD and asthma.

662
00:23:48.186 --> 00:23:49.456
It is amazing how many patients

663
00:23:49.456 --> 00:23:51.310
use these inhalers incorrectly.

664
00:23:51.310 --> 00:23:52.752
So have them come in,

665
00:23:52.752 --> 00:23:54.607
bring their inhaler and demonstrate

666
00:23:54.607 --> 00:23:55.940
in front of you.

667
00:23:57.083 --> 00:24:00.104
Next question, same patient.

668
00:24:00.104 --> 00:24:01.446
So your patient with COPD

669
00:24:01.446 --> 00:24:02.969
developed an upper respiratory infection

670
00:24:02.969 --> 00:24:03.802
last week.

671
00:24:03.802 --> 00:24:05.509
They now present with increased cough,

672
00:24:05.509 --> 00:24:07.282
yellow sputum and increasing dyspnea,

673
00:24:07.282 --> 00:24:08.350
and wheezing.

674
00:24:08.350 --> 00:24:10.919
Exam reveals no respiratory distress

675
00:24:10.919 --> 00:24:13.523
with an SAO2 of 89% on room air,

676
00:24:13.523 --> 00:24:15.141
and no signs of consolidation

677
00:24:15.141 --> 00:24:17.312
on lung auscultation.

678
00:24:17.312 --> 00:24:18.495
In addition to steroids,

679
00:24:18.495 --> 00:24:19.537
which one of the following

680
00:24:19.537 --> 00:24:20.443
would be most appropriate

681
00:24:20.443 --> 00:24:22.315
for you to prescribe at this time?

682
00:24:22.315 --> 00:24:24.021
A, Augmentin.

683
00:24:24.021 --> 00:24:24.938
B, Mucinex.

684
00:24:25.844 --> 00:24:27.220
C, Oxygen.

685
00:24:27.220 --> 00:24:28.803
Or D, Theophylline.

686
00:24:34.087 --> 00:24:34.920
Good.

687
00:24:34.920 --> 00:24:35.753
Augmentin.

688
00:24:35.753 --> 00:24:37.393
This is a classic case for needing antibiotics.

689
00:24:37.393 --> 00:24:38.517
Good.

690
00:24:38.517 --> 00:24:42.350
The SAO2 isn't low enough to prescribe oxygen.

691
00:24:43.344 --> 00:24:44.351
And no one uses...

692
00:24:44.351 --> 00:24:45.408
Does anyone use theophylline anymore?

693
00:24:45.408 --> 00:24:46.827
Theophylline is out.

694
00:24:46.827 --> 00:24:48.119
There's no reason to use theophylline anymore.

695
00:24:48.119 --> 00:24:49.119
Almost none.

696
00:24:50.526 --> 00:24:51.359
All right.

697
00:24:51.359 --> 00:24:52.959
So an acute COPD exacerbation

698
00:24:52.959 --> 00:24:54.191
worsening of symptoms.

699
00:24:54.191 --> 00:24:55.184
The most common cause

700
00:24:55.184 --> 00:24:56.908
is a viral upper respiratory infection.

701
00:24:56.908 --> 00:24:59.688
Increased dyspnea is one of the key symptoms.

702
00:24:59.688 --> 00:25:04.121
Don't forget to assess whether they need oxygen.

703
00:25:04.121 --> 00:25:06.321
Other things that can cause acute dyspnea.

704
00:25:06.321 --> 00:25:08.158
The differential is long here.

705
00:25:08.158 --> 00:25:09.810
Pneumonias, pneumo,

706
00:25:09.810 --> 00:25:12.079
pleural effusions, pulmonary emboli,

707
00:25:12.079 --> 00:25:14.031
pulmonary edema, cardiac arrhythmias.

708
00:25:14.031 --> 00:25:15.179
All of these things

709
00:25:15.179 --> 00:25:17.723
can contribute to and cause dyspnea.

710
00:25:17.723 --> 00:25:19.003
So they should be evaluated

711
00:25:19.003 --> 00:25:22.286
if you have clinical suspicion.

712
00:25:22.286 --> 00:25:25.075
COPD exacerbation classification hasn't changed.

713
00:25:25.075 --> 00:25:26.451
Mild, moderate or severe.

714
00:25:26.451 --> 00:25:28.205
That's pretty self-explanatory.

715
00:25:28.205 --> 00:25:29.616
Indications for admission.

716
00:25:29.616 --> 00:25:31.143
I've listed these here.

717
00:25:31.143 --> 00:25:32.974
For the purposes of the boards,

718
00:25:32.974 --> 00:25:35.197
they would make it very obvious to you

719
00:25:35.197 --> 00:25:36.309
if they felt the patient

720
00:25:36.309 --> 00:25:38.759
needed to be admitted to the hospital.

721
00:25:38.759 --> 00:25:42.881
Don't forget about assessing their O2 SATs.

722
00:25:42.881 --> 00:25:44.298
Titrate their O2.

723
00:25:46.022 --> 00:25:48.289
The SAO2 is greater than 88%

724
00:25:48.289 --> 00:25:51.425
in the presence of an exacerbation.

725
00:25:51.425 --> 00:25:52.768
Yes to bronchodilators.

726
00:25:52.768 --> 00:25:54.736
Yes to systemic steroids.

727
00:25:54.736 --> 00:25:56.179
Typically we're gonna use

728
00:25:56.179 --> 00:25:58.840
prednisone 40 milligrams a day for five days.

729
00:25:58.840 --> 00:26:00.889
That can be once a 20 milligrams BID

730
00:26:00.889 --> 00:26:02.577
or 40 milligrams once a day.

731
00:26:02.577 --> 00:26:04.447
What about antibiotics?

732
00:26:04.447 --> 00:26:05.500
Probably.

733
00:26:05.500 --> 00:26:07.448
Now for the purposes of the boards,

734
00:26:07.448 --> 00:26:10.434
they say that you should prescribe antibiotics

735
00:26:10.434 --> 00:26:12.772
if a patient presents with increased dyspnea,

736
00:26:12.772 --> 00:26:14.757
sputum volume or sputum purulence,

737
00:26:14.757 --> 00:26:16.056
that's the most important.

738
00:26:16.056 --> 00:26:17.179
Mrs. Smith may say,

739
00:26:17.179 --> 00:26:18.800
"You know, I cough up

740
00:26:18.800 --> 00:26:20.382
some clear sputum every day,

741
00:26:20.382 --> 00:26:23.029
but now it's yellow and green.

742
00:26:23.029 --> 00:26:26.446
That is a key change with a COPD patient.

743
00:26:27.740 --> 00:26:30.213
Which antibiotic you want to prescribe

744
00:26:30.213 --> 00:26:31.426
is up to you.

745
00:26:31.426 --> 00:26:32.943
The boards don't tell us.

746
00:26:32.943 --> 00:26:34.516
I will say that Augmentin

747
00:26:34.516 --> 00:26:36.933
would be commonly prescribed.

748
00:26:41.550 --> 00:26:45.097
Azithromycin, less commonly prescribed.

749
00:26:45.097 --> 00:26:48.859
You'll find that Zithromax is now out

750
00:26:48.859 --> 00:26:49.776
in medicine.

751
00:26:49.776 --> 00:26:51.282
It's out in respiratory.

752
00:26:51.282 --> 00:26:52.475
It's out in ENT.

753
00:26:52.475 --> 00:26:54.962
It's out in sexually transmitted infection.

754
00:26:54.962 --> 00:26:56.653
So it's now a second tier antibiotic,

755
00:26:56.653 --> 00:26:58.830
and we will discuss that this afternoon

756
00:26:58.830 --> 00:27:00.181
when we discuss pneumonias.

757
00:27:00.181 --> 00:27:01.014
Thank you.

758
00:27:01.014 --> 00:27:03.250
<v Announcer>Thank you very much, Dr. Conner.</v>

759
00:27:03.250 --> 00:27:05.230
(audience applauding)

760
00:27:05.230 --> 00:27:07.730
(logo chimes)

